A reflective, anthropomorphic fox sits peacefully at the base of a recently fallen tree, its trunk resting gently on the forest floor. The fox wears simple, well-kept clothing — earthy and natural, suggesting harmony with the woods. His posture is calm and contemplative, one hand lightly brushing the bark as though in quiet communion. Signs of renewal surround the fallen tree: tender seedlings sprouting between roots, small flowers blooming along cracks in the log, and young vines curling upward toward the light. Morning rays filter through the canopy, casting soft beams across the scene, creating an atmosphere of peace after loss.

In the style of a cinematic fantasy illustration that fuses the luminous elegance of Sky Doll with the warmth and charm of expressive Western cartoon sensibilities. Characters have soft, natural yet stylized proportions: rounded, friendly facial features subtly elongated for grace and emotional resonance; large almond-shaped luminous eyes with expressive brows; softly sculpted contours with subtle blush and airbrushed lips for depth and clarity.

Linework is smooth and clean with gentle variation in thickness, defining forms gracefully without harshness. Shading blends cel-style softness with airbrushed gradients, dewy highlights, and delicate rim lighting. Surfaces are digitally polished — no grain, no painterly texture. Lighting is balanced and cinematic, combining ambient glow with selective highlights to emphasize the fox’s gentle reflection. Background softened with light mist, faint sparkles, and floating particles to create a dreamy, magical atmosphere.

A throne built from addiction, a crown too heavy to bear. For #AiTheme2025Week36 – Unchecked Vices, I wanted to capture the weight of surrender when pleasure hardens into chains.

external.description:
Today, AWS announces the general availability of Organizational Notification Configurations for AWS User Notifications. This launch allows AWS Organizations users to centrally configure and view notifications across their organization. You can use the Management Account or Delegated Administrators (DAs) to configure and view notifications about accounts included in specific organizational units (OUs) or all accounts rolling up to an organization. Once configured, events from any of the member accounts will generate a notification in the Management Account. User Notifications supports up to 5 DAs.
 
 You can use this capability to setup notifications for any supported https://docs.aws.amazon.com/eventbridge/latest/userguide/eb-service-event-list.html. For example, you can setup a notification configuration to send a push notification to the https://aws.amazon.com/console/mobile/ anytime a user in any of the member accounts in your organization signs in to the console without MFA. Notifications will also be available in the Admin’s Console Notifications Center.
 
 This new capability is available in all https://aws.amazon.com/about-aws/global-infrastructure/regional-product-services/ where AWS User Notifications is available.
 
 To learn more about managing notifications across your organization with AWS User Notifications, please refer to the https://docs.aws.amazon.com/notifications/latest/userguide/managing-org-notifications.html.
external.title: Announcing general availability of Organizational Notification Configurations for AWS User Notifications

external.description:
AWS Control Tower and Control Catalog APIs now allow customers to use Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) addresses. With the new dual-stack endpoints, customers can connect to AWS Control Tower and over the public internet using IPv6, IPv4, or dual-stack clients. The existing AWS Control Tower endpoints supporting IPv4 will remain available for backwards compatibility.
 
 The continued growth of the Internet, particularly in the areas of mobile applications, connected devices, and IoT, has spurred an industry-wide move to IPv6. IPv6 increases the number of available addresses by several orders of magnitude so customers will no longer need to manage overlapping address spaces in their Amazon Virtual Private Cloud (Amazon VPC).
 
 Support for IPv6 on AWS Control Tower and Control Catalog API is available in all Regions where AWS Control Tower and Control Catalog API are available. For a full list of Regions where AWS Control Tower is available, see the https://aws.amazon.com/about-aws/global-infrastructure/regional-product-services/. To learn more on best practices for configuring IPv6 in your environment, visit the https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/ipv6-on-aws/internet-protocol-version-6.html. To learn more about AWS Control Tower, visit the https://docs.aws.amazon.com/controltower/latest/userguide/what-is-control-tower.html.
external.title: AWS Control Tower now supports Internet Protocol Version 6 (IPv6)
